  "response_text": "It begins with a pale title card for the television program. Large block letters read “DO YOU TRUST YOUR WIFE,” arranged in three lines, with flat star shapes scattered around the words. The picture is black and white, with the lettering dark against a light background.\n\nThe program title fades into a product display. A square Jell-O package appears centered over a busy patterned background filled with repeated words such as “BUSY DAY DESSERT.” The front of the box reads “JELL-O” at the top, “New” on a dark diagonal label, “INSTANT PUDDING” in large lettering, and “7 FLAVORS” along the bottom. The box remains prominent, slightly three-dimensional, as the busy-day wording repeats behind it.\n\nThe imagery shifts to a simple line-drawn animation on a plain light background. A clock-like symbol appears: two dark hands with arrowheads pivot from a central dot. The hands swing around rapidly, leaving faint circular rings behind them, visually suggesting time rushing by. A small cartoon car then enters from the right. Inside are two simplified cartoon figures, drawn with thin black outlines. The front figure has a long pointed nose and curly hair; a second smaller figure sits behind. The car moves across the scene while the clock hands continue to spin behind it.\n\nThe clock motif continues as the car exits. A cartoon adult figure appears, leaning forward with a mop or long-handled cleaning tool, as if mopping the floor. The figure has a simple triangular body, curly hair, and a pointed nose. The drawing is spare and humorous, with the body angled as though hurrying through a chore. Brief abstract vertical shapes appear during the sequence, then another cartoon domestic scene appears: the curly-haired adult stands with a basket tucked against one side while a small childlike figure stands nearby. The adult’s posture and the repeated clock arrows behind them continue the sense of a crowded, hurried day.\n\nA large oval clock face fills the scene, with a vertical arrowed hand running from bottom to top through a central dot. The same cartoon adult stands at the right edge, looking up toward the clock. The figure’s body droops slightly, suggesting fatigue or concern as the day reaches dinner time. The clock graphic transforms into a large circular shape, and the adult raises a hand to the face with a relieved, smiling expression.\n\nA product message then appears over the pale background. Large text reads “JELL-O,” and behind it, inside a soft oval, are the words “New INSTANT PUDDING.” A dark tilted label at lower left reads “No Cooking BUSY-DAY Dessert.” The Jell-O Instant Pudding box is then shown alone in three-quarter view, sitting against a plain light background. The same front-panel wording is visible: “JELL-O,” “New,” and “INSTANT PUDDING,” with the dark “No Cooking BUSY-DAY Dessert” label on the lower left of the box.\n\nThe commercial moves into a live-action preparation demonstration. A clear glass mixing bowl sits on a counter, partly filled with milk. To the right of the bowl lies an electric hand mixer with two metal beaters. A hand holds the Jell-O Instant Pudding box over the bowl and pours the dry pudding mix into the milk. Powder falls in a steady stream, forming pale mounds and darker patches on the milk’s surface. The package is then set down to the left of the bowl, front facing outward so the Jell-O branding remains visible.\n\nA hand brings the electric mixer over the bowl. The two beaters are lowered straight down into the milk and powder mixture. The beaters begin to turn, churning the contents; the surface ripples and thickens as the dry mix is drawn into the liquid. The box remains placed to the left as a visual reference while the bowl stays centered.\n\nThe prepared dessert is then presented on a round serving tray. Four footed glass dessert cups are arranged on small saucers, each filled with a smooth, light-colored pudding. The tops look softly mounded or swirled, with a creamy texture. A hand places one of the cups into the front center position, completing the arrangement. The tray has a polished, reflective surface and a slightly raised rim, giving the dessert presentation a tidy, formal serving-table look.\n\nThe final product display returns to the Jell-O Instant Pudding box against a pale background. Large floating words behind and above it read “GOOD GOOD” and “BUSY-DAY DESSERT.” The box again shows “JELL-O,” the dark diagonal “New” label, “INSTANT PUDDING,” and “7 FLAVORS” near the bottom, ending with the package centered as the main visual focus.",
